[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] CM applied over the lifecycle of a system provides visibility and control of its performance, functional, and physical attributes.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] CM verifies that a system performs as intended, and is documented in sufficient detail to support its projected life cycle.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] The CM process facilitates orderly management of system information and system changes for purposes such as to revise capability; improve performance, reliability, or maintainability; extend life; reduce costs; reduce risk and liability; or correct defects.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] The relatively minimal cost of implementing CM is returned manyfold in cost avoidance.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] The lack of CM (or its ineffectual implementation) can be very expensive and sometimes can have such catastrophic consequences such as failure of equipment or loss of life.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] CM emphasizes the functional relation between parts, subsystems, and systems for effectively controlling system change.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] It helps to verify that proposed changes are systematically considered to minimize adverse effects.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Changes to the system are proposed, evaluated, and implemented using a standardized, systematic approach that ensures consistency, and proposed changes are evaluated in terms of their anticipated impact on the entire system.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] CM verifies that changes are carried out as specified and that documentation of items and systems reflects their true configuration.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] A complete CM program includes provisions for the storing, tracking, and updating of all system information on a component, subsystem, and system basis.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] A structured CM program ensures that documentation (e.g., requirements, design, test, and acceptance documentation) for items is accurate and consistent with the actual physical design of the item.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] In many cases, without CM, the documentation exists but is not consistent with the item itself.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] For this reason, engineers, contractors, and management are frequently forced to develop documentation reflecting the actual status of the item before they can proceed with a change.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] This reverse engineering process is wasteful in terms of human and other resources and can be minimized or eliminated using CM.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Configuration management originated in the United States Department of Defense in the 1950s as a technical management discipline for hardware material items—and it is now a standard practice in virtually every industry.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] The CM process became its own technical discipline in the late 1960s when the DoD developed a series of military standards called the "480 series" (i.e., MIL-STD-480, MIL-STD-481 and MIL-STD-483) that were subsequently issued in the 1970s.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] This marked the beginning of what has now evolved into the most widely distributed and accepted standard on CM, ANSI–EIA–649–1998.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Many of these functions and models have redefined CM from its traditional holistic approach to technical management.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Some treat CM as being similar to a librarian activity and break out change control or change management as a separate or standalone discipline.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] CM is the practice of handling changes systematically so that a system maintains its integrity over time.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] CM implements the policies, procedures, techniques, and tools that manage, evaluate proposed changes, track change status, and maintain an inventory of system and support documents as the system changes.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] CM programs and plans provide technical and administrative direction to the development and implementation of the procedures, functions, services, tools, processes, and resources required to successfully develop and support a complex system.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] During system development, CM allows program management to track requirements throughout the life-cycle through acceptance and operations and maintenance.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] As changes inevitably occur in the requirements and design, they must be approved and documented, creating an accurate record of the system status.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Ideally the CM process is applied throughout the system life cycle.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Many professionals mix up or get confused with Asset management (AM, see also ISO/IEC 19770), where it inventories the assets on hand.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] The key difference between CM and AM is that the former does not manage the financial accounting aspect but the service that the system supports or in other words, that the latter (AM) is trying to realize value from an IT asset.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] The CM process for both hardware and software configuration items comprises five distinct disciplines as established in the MIL–HDBK–61A and in ANSI/EIA-649.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Members of an organization interested in applying a standard change-management process will employ these disciplines as policies and procedures for establishing baselines, manage and control change, and monitor and assess the effectiveness and correctness of progress.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] The IEEE 12207 process IEEE 12207.2 also has these activities and adds "Release management and delivery".
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Configuration Identification (CI): consists of setting and maintaining baselines, which define the system or subsystem architecture, components, and any developments at any point in time.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] It is the basis by which changes to any part of a system are identified, documented, and later tracked through design, development, testing, and final delivery.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] CI incrementally establishes and maintains the definitive current basis for Configuration Status Accounting (CSA) of a system and its configuration items (CIs) throughout their life cycle (development, production, deployment, and operational support) until disposal.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Configuration Control: includes the evaluation of all change-requests and change-proposals, and their subsequent approval or disapproval.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] It covers the process of controlling modifications to the system's design, hardware, firmware, software, and documentation.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Configuration Status Accounting: includes the process of recording and reporting configuration item descriptions (e.g., hardware, software, firmware, etc.) and all departures from the baseline during design and production.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] In the event of suspected problems, operators can quickly verify baseline configuration and approved modifications.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Configuration Verification and Audit: an independent review of hardware and software for the purpose of assessing compliance with established performance requirements, commercial and appropriate military standards, and functional, allocated, and product baselines.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Configuration audits verify that the system and subsystem configuration documentation complies with the functional and physical performance characteristics before acceptance into an architectural baseline.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] The software configuration management (SCM) process is looked upon by practitioners as the best solution to handling changes in software projects.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] It identifies the functional and physical attributes of software at various points in time, and performs systematic control of changes to the identified attributes for the purpose of maintaining software integrity and traceability throughout the software development life cycle.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] The SCM process further defines the need to trace changes, and the ability to verify that the final delivered software has all of the planned enhancements that are supposed to be included in the release.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] It identifies four procedures that must be defined for each software project to ensure that a sound SCM process is implemented.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] These terms and definitions can change somewhat from standard to standard.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] ITIL specifies the use of a configuration management system (CMS) or configuration management database (CMDB) as a means of achieving industry best practices for Configuration Management.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] CMS helps manage a federated collection of CMDBs.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] The benefits of a CMS/CMDB includes being able to perform functions like root cause analysis, impact analysis, change management, and current state assessment for future state strategy development.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] For information assurance, CM can be defined as the management of security features and assurances through control of changes made to hardware, software, firmware, documentation, test, test fixtures, and test documentation throughout the life cycle of an information system.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] For example, configuration requirements may be different for a network firewall that functions as part of an organization's Internet boundary versus one that functions as an internal local network firewall.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Configuration management is used to maintain an understanding of the status of complex assets with a view to maintaining the highest level of serviceability for the lowest cost.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Specifically, it aims to ensure that operations are not disrupted due to the asset (or parts of the asset) overrunning limits of planned lifespan or below quality levels.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] In the military, this type of activity is often classed as "mission readiness", and seeks to define which assets are available and for which type of mission; a classic example is whether aircraft on board an aircraft carrier are equipped with bombs for ground support or missiles for defense.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Configuration management can be used to maintain OS configuration files.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Many of these systems utilize Infrastructure as Code to define and maintain configuration.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] The Promise theory of configuration maintenance was developed by Mark Burgess, with a practical implementation on present day computer systems in the software CFEngine able to perform real time repair as well as preventive maintenance.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Understanding the "as is" state of an asset and its major components is an essential element in preventive maintenance as used in maintenance, repair, and overhaul and enterprise asset management systems.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Complex assets such as aircraft, ships, industrial machinery etc. depend on many different components being serviceable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] This serviceability is often defined in terms of the amount of usage the component has had since it was new, since fitted, since repaired, the amount of use it has had over its life and several other limiting factors.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Understanding how near the end of their life each of these components is has been a major undertaking involving labor-intensive record keeping until recent developments in software.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Many types of component use electronic sensors to capture data which provides live condition monitoring.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] This data is analyzed on board or at a remote location by computer to evaluate its current serviceability and increasingly its likely future state using algorithms which predict potential future failures based on previous examples of failure through field experience and modeling.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] This is the basis for "predictive maintenance".
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Availability of accurate and timely data is essential in order for CM to provide operational value and a lack of this can often be a limiting factor.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Capturing and disseminating the operating data to the various support organizations is becoming an industry in itself.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] The consumers of this data have grown more numerous and complex with the growth of programs offered by original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] These are designed to offer operators guaranteed availability and make the picture more complex with the operator managing the asset but the OEM taking on the liability to ensure its serviceability.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] More recently configuration management has been applied to large construction projects which can often be very complex and have a huge number of details and changes that need to be documented.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] Construction agencies such as the Federal Highway Administration have used configuration management for their infrastructure projects.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] There are construction-based configuration management tools that aim to document change orders and RFIs in order to ensure a project stays on schedule and on budget.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] These programs can also store information to aid in the maintenance and modification of the infrastructure when it is completed.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/configuration-management] This study yielded results indicating a benefit to using configuration management on projects of this nature.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In object-oriented (OO) and functional programming, an **immutable object** (unchangeable object) is an object whose state cannot be modified after it is created.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] This is in contrast to a **mutable object** (changeable object), which can be modified after it is created.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In some cases, an object is considered immutable even if some internally used attributes change, but the object's state appears unchanging from an external point of view.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] For example, an object that uses memoization to cache the results of expensive computations could still be considered an immutable object.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Strings and other concrete objects are typically expressed as immutable objects to improve readability and runtime efficiency in object-oriented programming.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Immutable objects are also useful because they are inherently thread-safe.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Other benefits are that they are simpler to understand and reason about and offer higher security than mutable objects.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In imperative programming, values held in program variables whose content never changes are known as *constants* to differentiate them from variables that could be altered during execution.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Examples include conversion factors from meters to feet, or the value of pi to several decimal places.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Read-only fields may be calculated when the program runs (unlike constants, which are known beforehand), but never change after they are initialized.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Sometimes, one talks of certain *fields* of an object being immutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] This means that there is no way to change those parts of the object state, even though other parts of the object may be changeable (*weakly immutable*).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] If all fields are immutable, then the object is immutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] If the whole object cannot be extended by another class, the object is called *strongly immutable*.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] This might, for example, help to explicitly enforce certain invariants about certain data in the object staying the same through the lifetime of the object.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In some languages, this is done with a keyword (e.g.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] `const` in C++, `final` in Java) that designates the field as immutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Some languages reverse it: in OCaml, fields of an object or record are by default immutable, and must be explicitly marked with `mutable` to be so.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In most object-oriented languages, objects can be referred to using references.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Some examples of such languages are Java, C++, C#, VB.NET, and many scripting languages, such as Perl, Python, and Ruby.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In this case, it matters whether the state of an object can vary when objects are shared via references.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] If an object is known to be immutable, it is preferred to create a reference of it instead of copying the entire object.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] This is done to conserve memory by preventing data duplication and avoid calls to constructors and destructors; it also results in a potential boost in execution speed.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] The reference copying technique is much more difficult to use for mutable objects, because if any user of a mutable object reference changes it, all other users of that reference see the change.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] If this is not the intended effect, it can be difficult to notify the other users to have them respond correctly.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In these situations, defensive copying of the entire object rather than the reference is usually an easy but costly solution.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] The observer pattern is an alternative technique for handling changes to mutable objects.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] A technique that blends the advantages of **mutable** and **immutable** objects, and is supported directly in almost all modern hardware, is copy-on-write (COW).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Using this technique, when a user asks the system to copy an object, it instead merely creates a new reference that still points to the same object.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] As soon as a user attempts to modify the object through a particular reference, the system makes a real copy, applies the modification to that, and sets the reference to refer to the new copy.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] The other users are unaffected, because they still refer to the original object.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Therefore, under COW, all users appear to have a mutable version of their objects, although in the case that users do not modify their objects, the space-saving and speed advantages of immutable objects are preserved.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Copy-on-write is popular in virtual memory systems because it allows them to save memory space while still correctly handling anything an application program might do.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] The practice of always using references in place of copies of equal objects is known as *interning*.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] If interning is used, two objects are considered equal if and only if their references, typically represented as pointers or integers, are equal.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Some languages do this automatically: for example, Python automatically interns short strings.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] If the algorithm that implements interning is guaranteed to do so in every case that it is possible, then comparing objects for equality is reduced to comparing their pointers – a substantial gain in speed in most applications.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] (Even if the algorithm is not guaranteed to be comprehensive, there still exists the possibility of a fast path case improvement when the objects are equal and use the same reference.) Interning is generally only useful for immutable objects.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Immutable objects can be useful in multi-threaded applications.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Multiple threads can act on data represented by immutable objects without concern of the data being changed by other threads.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Immutable objects are therefore considered more *thread-safe* than mutable objects.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Immutability does not imply that the object as stored in the computer's memory is unwriteable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Rather, immutability is a compile-time construct that indicates what a programmer can do through the normal interface of the object, not necessarily what they can absolutely do (for instance, by circumventing the type system or violating const correctness in C or C++).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In Python, Java and the .NET Framework, strings are immutable objects.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Both Java and the .NET Framework have mutable versions of string.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In Java these are `StringBuffer` and `StringBuilder` (mutable versions of Java `String`) and in .NET this is `StringBuilder` (mutable version of .Net `String`).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Python 3 has a mutable string (bytes) variant, named `bytearray`.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Additionally, all of the primitive wrapper classes in Java are immutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Similar patterns are the Immutable Interface and Immutable Wrapper.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In pure functional programming languages it is not possible to create mutable objects without extending the language (e.g. via a mutable references library or a foreign function interface), so all objects are immutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In Ada, any object is declared either *variable* (i.e. mutable; typically the implicit default), or `constant` (i.e. immutable) via the `constant` keyword.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Subprogram parameters are immutable in the *in* mode, and mutable in the *in out* and *out* modes.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In C# one can enforce immutability of the fields of a class with the `readonly` statement.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] By enforcing all the fields as immutable, the type becomes an immutable type.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In C++, a const-correct implementation of `ShoppingCart` would allow the user to create instances of the class and then use them as either `const` (immutable) or mutable, as desired, by providing two different versions of the `items()` method.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Note that, when there is a data member that is a pointer or reference to another object, then it is possible to mutate the object pointed to or referenced only within a non-const method.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] C++ also provides abstract (as opposed to bitwise) immutability via the `mutable` keyword, which lets a member variable be changed from within a `const` method.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In D, there exist two type qualifiers, `const` and `immutable`, for variables that cannot be changed.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Unlike C++'s `const`, Java's `final`, and C#'s `readonly`, they are transitive and recursively apply to anything reachable through references of such a variable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] The difference between `const` and `immutable` is what they apply to: `const` is a property of the variable: there might legally exist mutable references to referred value, i.e. the value can actually change.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In contrast, `immutable` is a property of the referred value: the value and anything transitively reachable from it cannot change (without breaking the type system, leading to undefined behavior).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Any reference of that value must be marked `const` or `immutable`.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Basically for any unqualified type `T`, `const(T)` is the disjoint union of `T` (mutable) and `immutable(T)`.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] For a mutable `Example` object, its `mutableField` can be written to.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] For a `const(Example)` object, `mutableField` cannot be modified, it inherits `const`; `immutableField` is still immutable as it is the stronger guarantee.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] For an `immutable(Example)`, all fields are immutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Inside the braces, `c` might refer to the same object as `m`, so mutations to `m` could indirectly change `c` as well.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Also, `c` might refer to the same object as `i`, but since the value then is immutable, there are no changes.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] However, `m` and `i` cannot legally refer to the same object.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In the language of guarantees, mutable has no guarantees (the function might change the object), `const` is an outward-only guarantee that the function will not change anything, and `immutable` is a bidirectional guarantee (the function will not change the value and the caller must not change it).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Values that are `const` or `immutable` must be initialized by direct assignment at the point of declaration or by a constructor.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Because `const` parameters forget if the value was mutable or not, a similar construct, `inout`, acts, in a sense, as a variable for mutability information.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] A function of type `const(S) function(const(T))` returns `const(S)` typed values for mutable, const and immutable arguments.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In contrast, a function of type `inout(S) function(inout(T))` returns `S` for mutable `T` arguments, `const(S)` for `const(T)` values, and `immutable(S)` for `immutable(T)` values.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Casting immutable values to mutable inflicts undefined behavior upon change, even if the original value comes from a mutable origin.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Casting mutable values to immutable can be legal when there remain no mutable references afterward.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] The type `string` is an alias for `immutable(char)[]`, i.e. a typed slice of memory of immutable characters.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Making substrings is cheap, as it just copies and modifies a pointer and a length filed, and safe, as the underlying data cannot be changed.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Objects of type `const(char)[]` can refer to strings, but also to mutable buffers.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Making a shallow copy of a const or immutable value removes the outer layer of immutability: Copying an immutable string (`immutable(char[])`) returns a string (`immutable(char)[]`).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] The immutable pointer and length are being copied and the copies are mutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] The referred data has not been copied and keeps its qualifier, in the example `immutable`.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] It can be stripped by making a depper copy, e.g. using the `dup` function.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] The method `toLowerCase()` does not change the data "ABC" that `s` contains.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Instead, a new String object is instantiated and given the data "abc" during its construction.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] A reference to this String object is returned by the `toLowerCase()` method.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Now the String `s` references a new String object that contains "abc".
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] There is nothing in the syntax of the *declaration* of the class String that enforces it as immutable; rather, none of the String class's methods ever affect the data that a String object contains, thus making it immutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] The keyword `final` (detailed article) is used in implementing immutable primitive types and object references, but it cannot, by itself, make *the objects themselves* immutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Primitive type variables (`int`, `long`, `short`, etc.) can be reassigned after being defined.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Reference types cannot be made immutable just by using the `final` keyword.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Primitive wrappers (`Integer`, `Long`, `Short`, `Double`, `Float`, `Character`, `Byte`, `Boolean`) are also all immutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Immutable classes can be implemented by following a few simple guidelines.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In JavaScript, all primitive types (Undefined, Null, Boolean, Number, BigInt, String, Symbol) are immutable, but custom objects are generally mutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] To simulate immutability in an object, one may define properties as read-only (writable: false).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] However, the approach above still lets new properties be added.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Alternatively, one may use Object.freeze to make existing objects immutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] With the implementation of ECMA262, JavaScript has the ability to create immutable references that cannot be reassigned.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] However, using a `const` declaration doesn't mean that value of the read-only reference is immutable, just that the name cannot be assigned to a new value.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] The use of immutable state has become a rising trend in JavaScript since the introduction of React, which favours Flux-like state management patterns such as Redux.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In PHP have readonly properties since version 8.1 and readonly classes since version 8.2.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In Python, some built-in types (numbers, Booleans, strings, tuples, frozensets) are immutable, but custom classes are generally mutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] The standard library helpers `collections.namedtuple` and `typing.NamedTuple`, available from Python 3.6 onward, create simple immutable classes.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Introduced in Python 3.7, `dataclasses` allow developers to emulate immutability with frozen instances.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] If a frozen dataclass is built, `dataclasses` will override `__setattr__()` and `__delattr__()` to raise `FrozenInstanceError` if invoked.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Racket substantially diverges from other Scheme implementations by making its core pair type ("cons cells") immutable.
