[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Rust's ownership system allows developers to declare immutable variables, and pass immutable references.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] By default, all variables and references are immutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Mutable variables and references are explicitly created with the `mut` keyword.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Constant items in Rust are always immutable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] In Scala, any entity (narrowly, a binding) can be defined as mutable or immutable: in the declaration, one can use `val` (value) for immutable entities and `var` (variable) for mutable ones.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/immutable-object] Note that even though an immutable binding can not be reassigned, it may still refer to a mutable object and it is still possible to call mutating methods on that object: the *binding* is immutable, but the underlying *object* may be mutable.
