[src:immutable-infrastructure/packer-intro] This introduction describes Packer benefits and how you can get started with it.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/packer-intro] Packer is a community tool for creating identical machine images for multiple platforms from a single source configuration.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/packer-intro] Packer is lightweight, runs on every major operating system, and is highly performant, creating machine images for multiple platforms in parallel.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/packer-intro] Packer does not replace configuration management like Chef or Puppet.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/packer-intro] In fact, when building images, Packer is able to use tools like Chef or Puppet to install software onto the image.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/packer-intro] A *machine image* is a single static unit that contains a pre-configured operating system and installed software which is used to quickly create new running machines.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/packer-intro] Machine image formats change for each platform.
