[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] In computing, a **system image** is a serialized copy of the entire state of a computer system stored in some non-volatile form, such as a binary compressed file.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] If a system has all its state written to a disk (i.e. on a disk image), then a system image can be produced by copying the disk to a file elsewhere, often with disk cloning applications.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] A system is said to be capable of using system images if it can be shut down and later restored to exactly the same state.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] In such cases, system images can be used for backup.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] Hibernation is an example that uses an image of the computer's entire RAM.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] A process image is a copy of a given process's state at a given point in time.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] It is often used to create persistence within an otherwise volatile system.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] A common example is a database management system (DBMS).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] Most DBMS can store the state of its database or databases to a file before being closed down (see database dump).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] The DBMS can then be restarted later with the information in the database intact and proceed as though the software had never stopped.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] Another example would be the hibernate feature of many operating systems.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] Here, the state of all RAM memory is stored to disk, the computer is brought into an energy saving mode, then later restored to normal operation.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] Some emulators provide a facility to save an image of the system being emulated.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] In video gaming this is often referred to as a savestate.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] Another use is code mobility: a mobile agent can migrate between machines by having its state saved, then copying the data to another machine and restarting there.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] Some programming languages provide a command to take a system image of a program.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] This is normally a standard feature in Smalltalk (inspired by FLEX) and Lisp, among other languages.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] Development in these languages is often quite different from many other programming languages.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] For example, in Lisp the programmer may load packages or other code into a running Lisp implementation using the read-eval-print loop, which usually compiles the programs.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] Data is loaded into the running Lisp system.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] The programmer may then dump a system image, containing that pre-compiled and possibly customized code—and also all loaded application data.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] Often this image is an executable, and can be run on other machines.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] Similar, Lisp Machines were booted from Lisp images, called Worlds.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] The World contains the complete operating system, its applications and its data in a single file.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] It was also possible to save incremental Worlds, that contain only the changes from some base World.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] Before saving the World, the Lisp Machine operating system could optimize the contents of memory (better memory layout, compacting data structures, sorting data, ...).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/system-image] Although its purpose is different, a "system image" is often similar in structure to a core dump.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] In computing, a **virtual machine** (**VM**) is the virtualization or emulation of a computer system.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are based on computer architectures and provide the functionality of a physical computer.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Their implementations may involve specialized hardware, software, or a combination of the two.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Some virtual machine emulators, such as QEMU and video game console emulators, are designed to also emulate (or "virtually imitate") different system architectures, thus allowing execution of software applications and operating systems written for another CPU or architecture.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] OS-level virtualization allows the resources of a computer to be partitioned via the kernel.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] The terms are not universally interchangeable.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] A 'virtual machine' was originally defined by Popek and Goldberg as "an efficient, isolated duplicate of a real computer machine." Current use includes virtual machines that have no direct correspondence to any real hardware.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] The physical, "real-world" hardware running the VM is generally referred to as the 'host', and the virtual machine emulated on that machine is generally referred to as the 'guest'.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] A host can emulate several guests, each of which can emulate different operating systems and hardware platforms.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] The desire to run multiple operating systems was the initial motive for virtual machines, so as to allow time-sharing among several single-tasking operating systems.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] In some respects, a system virtual machine can be considered a generalization of the concept of virtual memory that historically preceded it.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] IBM's CP/CMS, the first systems to allow full virtualization, implemented time sharing by providing each user with a single-user operating system, the Conversational Monitor System (CMS).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Unlike virtual memory, a system virtual machine entitled the user to write privileged instructions in their code.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] This approach had certain advantages, such as adding input/output devices not allowed by the standard system.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] As technology evolves virtual memory for purposes of virtualization, new systems of memory overcommitment may be applied to manage memory sharing among multiple virtual machines on one computer operating system.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] It may be possible to share *memory pages* that have identical contents among multiple virtual machines that run on the same physical machine, what may result in mapping them to the same physical page by a technique termed kernel same-page merging (KSM).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] This is especially useful for read-only pages, such as those holding code segments, which is the case for multiple virtual machines running the same or similar software, software libraries, web servers, middleware components, etc.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] The guest operating systems do not need to be compliant with the host hardware, thus making it possible to run different operating systems on the same computer (e.g., Windows, Linux, or prior versions of an operating system) to support future software.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] The use of virtual machines to support separate guest operating systems is popular in regard to embedded systems.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] A typical use would be to run a real-time operating system simultaneously with a preferred complex operating system, such as Linux or Windows.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Another use would be for novel and unproven software still in the developmental stage, so it runs inside a sandbox.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Virtual machines have other advantages for operating system development and may include improved debugging access and faster reboots.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Multiple VMs running their own guest operating system are frequently engaged for server consolidation.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] A **process virtual machine**, sometimes called an *application virtual machine*, or *Managed Runtime Environment* (MRE), runs as a normal application inside a host OS and supports a single process.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] It is created when that process is started and deleted when it is closed.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Its purpose is to provide a platform-independent programming environment that abstracts away details of the underlying hardware or operating system and allows a program to execute in the same way on any platform.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] A process VM provides a high-level abstraction – that of a high-level programming language (compared to the low-level ISA abstraction of the system VM).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Process VMs are implemented using an interpreter; performance comparable to compiled programming languages can be achieved by the use of just-in-time compilation.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] This type of VM has become popular with the Java programming language, which is implemented using the Java virtual machine.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Other examples include the Parrot virtual machine and the .NET Framework, which runs on a VM called the Common Language Runtime.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] All of them can serve as an abstraction layer for any computer language.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] A special case of process VMs are systems that abstract over the communication mechanisms of a (potentially heterogeneous) computer cluster.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Such a VM does not consist of a single process, but one process per physical machine in the cluster.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] They are designed to ease the task of programming concurrent applications by letting the programmer focus on algorithms rather than the communication mechanisms provided by the interconnect and the OS.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] They do not hide the fact that communication takes place, and as such do not attempt to present the cluster as a single machine.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Unlike other process VMs, these systems do not provide a specific programming language, but are embedded in an existing language; typically such a system provides bindings for several languages (e.g., C and Fortran).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Examples are Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM) and Message Passing Interface (MPI).
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Both system virtual machines and process virtual machines date to the 1960s and remain areas of active development.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Significant advances occurred in the implementation of Smalltalk-80, particularly the Deutsch/Schiffmann implementation which pushed just-in-time (JIT) compilation forward as an implementation approach that uses process virtual machine.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Later notable Smalltalk VMs were VisualWorks, the Squeak Virtual Machine, and Strongtalk.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] A related language that produced a lot of virtual machine innovation was the Self programming language, which pioneered adaptive optimization and generational garbage collection.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] These techniques proved commercially successful in 1999 in the HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Other innovations include a register-based virtual machine, to better match the underlying hardware, rather than a stack-based virtual machine, which is a closer match for the programming language; in 1995, this was pioneered by the Dis virtual machine for the Limbo language.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] In full virtualization, the virtual machine simulates enough hardware to allow an unmodified "guest" OS (one designed for the same instruction set) to be run in isolation.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] This approach was pioneered in 1966 with the IBM CP-40 and CP-67, predecessors of the VM family.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] In hardware-assisted virtualization, the hardware provides architectural support that facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system offered by IBM as an official product.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD provided additional hardware to support virtualization.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Sun Microsystems (acquired by Oracle Corporation) added similar features in their UltraSPARC T-Series processors in 2005.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Examples of virtualization platforms adapted to such hardware include KVM, VMware Workstation, VMware Fusion, Hyper-V, Windows Virtual PC, Xen, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Oracle VM Server for SPARC, VirtualBox and Parallels Workstation.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] In 2006, first-generation 32- and 64-bit x86 hardware support was found to rarely offer performance advantages over software virtualization.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] In OS-level virtualization, a physical server is virtualized at the operating system level, enabling multiple isolated and secure virtualized servers to run on a single physical server.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] The "guest" operating system environments share the same running instance of the operating system as the host system.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Thus, the same operating system kernel is also used to implement the "guest" environments, and applications running in a given "guest" environment view it as a stand-alone system.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] The pioneer implementation was FreeBSD jails; other examples include Docker, Solaris Containers, OpenVZ, Linux-VServer, LXC, AIX Workload Partitions, Parallels Virtuozzo Containers, and iCore Virtual Accounts.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] A *snapshot* is a state of a virtual machine, and generally its storage devices, at an exact point in time.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] A snapshot enables the virtual machine's state at the time of the snapshot to be restored later, effectively undoing any changes that occurred afterwards.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] This capability is useful as a backup technique, for example, prior to performing a risky operation.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Virtual machines frequently use virtual disks for their storage; in a very simple example, a 10-gigabyte hard disk drive is simulated with a 10-gigabyte flat file.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Any requests by the VM for a location on its physical disk are transparently translated into an operation on the corresponding file.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Once such a translation layer is present, however, it is possible to intercept the operations and send them to different files, depending on various criteria.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Every time a snapshot is taken, a new file is created, and used as an overlay for its predecessors.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] New data is written to the topmost overlay; reading existing data, however, needs the overlay hierarchy to be scanned, resulting in accessing the most recent version.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Thus, the entire stack of snapshots is virtually a single coherent disk; in that sense, creating snapshots works similarly to the incremental backup technique.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Other components of a virtual machine can also be included in a snapshot, such as the contents of its random-access memory (RAM), BIOS settings, or its configuration settings.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] "Save state" feature in video game console emulators is an example of such snapshots.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Restoring a snapshot consists of discarding or disregarding all overlay layers that are added after that snapshot, and directing all new changes to a new overlay.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] The snapshots described above can be moved to another host machine with its own hypervisor; when the VM is temporarily stopped, snapshotted, moved, and then resumed on the new host, this is known as migration.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] If the older snapshots are kept in sync regularly, this operation can be quite fast, and allow the VM to provide uninterrupted service while its prior physical host is, for example, taken down for physical maintenance.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Similar to the migration mechanism described above, failover allows the VM to continue operations if the host fails.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Generally it occurs if the migration has stopped working.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] However, in this case, the VM continues operation from the *last-known* coherent state, rather than the *current* state, based on whatever materials the backup server was last provided with.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Nested virtualization refers to the ability of running a virtual machine within another, having this general concept extendable to an arbitrary depth.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] In other words, nested virtualization refers to running one or more hypervisors inside another hypervisor.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] The nature of a nested guest virtual machine does not need to be homogeneous with its host virtual machine; for example, application virtualization can be deployed within a virtual machine created by using hardware virtualization.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Furthermore, moving already existing virtualized environments into a cloud, following the Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) approach, is much more complicated if the destination IaaS platform does not support nested virtualization.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] The way nested virtualization can be implemented on a particular computer architecture depends on supported hardware-assisted virtualization capabilities.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] If a particular architecture does not provide hardware support required for nested virtualization, various software techniques are employed to enable it.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Over time, more architectures gain required hardware support; for example, since the Haswell microarchitecture (announced in 2013), Intel started to include VMCS shadowing as a technology that accelerates nested virtualization.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are frequently used to isolate applications from one another for security.
[src:immutable-infrastructure/virtual-machine] This architectural design (used by Qubes OS, Whonix, KickSecure, and Dangerzone) can prevent the spread of malware from one compromised system (e.g. an email client opening an infected document) to another system (e.g. a password manager).
